p://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/post-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(23,1,'2020-06-26 15:32:14','2020-06-26 18:32:14','','Survivors of PNPC Dam Collapse in Laos Flee Deteriorating Relocation Centers','','inherit','closed','closed','','21-revision-v1','','','2020-06-26 15:32:14','2020-06-26 18:32:14','',21,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/26/21-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(24,1,'2020-06-26 15:33:27','2020-06-26 18:33:27','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Southeast Asia is one of the biggest sources of plastic waste from land to the ocean, and Thailand is among the top five contributors. In January, Thailand placed a ban on single-use plastic, and was looking to reduce its plastic waste by 30% this year.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the COVID-19 pandemic and the resulting lockdown has led to a huge rise in the country’s plastic waste. According to the Thailand Environment Institute (TEI), the average amount of plastic waste went from 2,120 tons per day in 2019 to approximately 3,440 tons per day between January and April 2020. The rise in the month of April alone was nearly 62%.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:jeo-theme/custom-image-block-editor {\"title\":\"Uma mulher coletando cafe na Amazonia Brasileira\",\"mediaID\":110,\"mediaURL\":\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/cambodia-4.jpg\",\"mediaDescription\":\"CNN Brasil / Fotógrafo Isaque\"} -->\n<div class=\"image-block-container\"><image-block title=\"Uma mulher coletando cafe na Amazonia Brasileira\" mediaurl=\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/cambodia-4.jpg\" mediadescription=\"CNN Brasil / Fotógrafo Isaque\"></image-block></div>\n<!-- /wp:jeo-theme/custom-image-block-editor -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the COVID-19 pandemic and the resulting lockdown has led to a huge rise in the country’s plastic waste. According to the Thailand Environment Institute (TEI), the average amount of plastic waste went from 2,120 tons per day in 2019 to approximately 3,440 tons per day between January and April 2020. The rise in the month of April alone was nearly 62%.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Committee votes to ban harmful pesticides from June 1','','publish','open','open','','committee-votes-to-ban-harmful-pesticides-from-june-1','','','2020-07-01 11:02:52','2020-07-01 14:02:52','',0,'http://localhost/?p=24',0,'post','',0),(25,1,'2020-06-26 15:32:50','2020-06-26 18:32:50','','post-4','','inherit','open','closed','','post-4','','','2020-06-26 15:32:50','2020-06-26 18:32:50','',24,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/post-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(26,1,'2020-06-26 15:33:27','2020-06-26 18:33:27','','Committee votes to ban harmful pesticides from June 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','24-revision-v1','','','2020-06-26 15:33:27','2020-06-26 18:33:27','',24,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/26/24-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(27,2,'2020-06-26 15:34:02','2020-06-26 18:34:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Every human on Earth&nbsp;is ingesting nearly 2,000 particles of plastic a week. These tiny pieces enter our unwitting bodies from tap water, food, and even the air, according to an alarming academic study sponsored by the World Wildlife Fund for Nature, dosing us with five grams of plastics.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With new legislation, the Break Free From Plastic&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.rollingstone.com/t/pollution/\">Pollution</a>&nbsp;Act of 2020, Udall is attempting to marshal Washington into a confrontation with the plastics industry, and to force companies that profit from plastics to take accountability for the waste they create. Unveiled in February, the bill would ban many single-use plastics and force corporations to finance “end of life” programs to keep plastic out of the environment. “We’re going back to that principle,” the senator tells&nbsp;<em>Rolling Stone</em>. “The polluter pays.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:cover {\"url\":\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek.jpg\",\"id\":404,\"hasParallax\":true,\"dimRatio\":70,\"align\":\"full\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-cover alignfull has-background-dim-70 has-background-dim has-parallax\" style=\"background-image:url(http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek.jpg)\"><div class=\"wp-block-cover__inner-container\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"placeholder\":\"Escreva o título...\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\"></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote {\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote is-style-default\"><p>“We are consuming a credit card’s worth of plastic each week,” Udall says. At events with constituents, he will brandish a Visa from his wallet and declare, “You’re eating this, folks!”</p><cite><strong>Quotes Author</strong></cite></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:cover -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Americans have occasionally crusaded against “problem plastics” — scapegoating packing peanuts, grocery bags, or drinking straws for the sins of our unsustainable consumer economy. We’ve been slow to recognize that we’re actually in the midst of a plastic pandemic. Over the past 70 years, we’ve gotten hooked on disposable goods and packaging — as plastics became the lifeblood of an American culture of speed, convenience, and disposability that’s conquered the globe. Plastic contains our hot coffee and frozen dinners. It is the material of childhood, from Pampers to Playmobil to PlayStation 4. It cloaks our e-commerce purchases and is woven into our sneakers, fast fashion, and business fleece. Humans are now using a million plastic bottles a minute, and 500 billion plastic bags a year — including those we use to bag up our plastic-laden trash.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the world’s plastic waste is not so easily contained. Massive quantities of this forever material are spilling into the oceans — the equivalent of a dump-truck load every minute. Plastic is also fouling our mountains, our farmland, and spiraling into an unmitigatable environmental disaster. John Hocevar is a marine biologist who leads the Oceans Campaign for Greenpeace, and spearheaded the group’s response to the BP oil spill in the Gulf. Increasingly, his work has centered on plastics. “This is a much bigger problem than ‘just’ an ocean issue, or even a pollution issue,” he says. “We’ve found plastic everywhere we’ve ever looked. It’s in the Arctic and the Antarctic and in the middle of the Pacific. It’s in the Pyrenees and in the Rockies. It’s settling out of the air. It’s raining down on us.”<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>The worst of our global plastics</strong> map</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>ALSO IN THIS REGION</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-default\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"postLayout\":\"grid\",\"typeScale\":2} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#f5f5f5\",\"align\":\"full\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group alignfull has-background\" style=\"background-color:#f5f5f5\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\"><!-- wp:heading {\"align\":\"center\",\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"has-text-align-center\">Título da galeria em H3</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[485,488,491,494,478,475,472,375,381,215,201,205],\"columns\":4} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-4 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/pasifik4a.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"485\" data-full-url=\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/pasifik4a.jpg\" data-link=\"http://localhost/index.php/20