"imageScale\":2} /--></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:button {\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"textColor\":\"dark-gray\",\"borderRadius\":0,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button aligncenter\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link has-text-color has-dark-gray-color has-background has-white-background-color no-border-radius\" href=\"/mekong-development\">SEE MORE</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column {\"width\":30} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:30%\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->','Homepage','','inherit','closed','closed','','7-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:22:50','2020-06-29 16:22:50','',7,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/7-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(101,1,'2020-06-29 13:24:14','2020-06-29 16:24:14','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With merely one of 10 people in the Philippines having access to clean water, it’s no surprise that waterborne diseases, particularly diarrhea, is killing over&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.who.int/philippines/news/feature-stories/detail/water-shortage-in-the-philippines-threatens-sustainable-development-and-health\">139 000 people</a>&nbsp;in the country ever year. If Covid-19 is now added to the list – as other studies have previously&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.sciencealert.com/latest-coronavirus-study-suggests-it-can-also-be-spread-through-poop\">warned</a>&nbsp;– fighting the virus effectively requires a wholistic approach that tackles the issue of reducing water pollution and providing alternative water supplies at the same time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The solution most city residents have been resorting to for years – in Manila and other cities across the ASEAN region – is the use of bottled water as a source of potable liquid independent of public supplies. Especially in times of public health emergencies like the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic, relying on bottled water is a safer option to prevent waterborne infections. As long as the government is&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.ibon.org/ensure-sufficient-safe-and-accessible-water-during-covid-19-crisis/\">unable</a>&nbsp;to guarantee “improved drinking water sources”, which the UN defines as “protected by outside contamination, particularly fecal matter”, this often remains the only option while deeper reforms to public infrastructure are being enacted.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','With merely one of 10 people in the Philippines having access to clean water','','publish','open','open','','with-merely-one-of-10-people-in-the-philippines-having-access-to-clean-water','','','2020-06-30 11:13:58','2020-06-30 14:13:58','',0,'http://localhost/?p=101',0,'post','',0),(102,1,'2020-06-29 13:24:14','2020-06-29 16:24:14','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With merely one of 10 people in the Philippines having access to clean water, it’s no surprise that waterborne diseases, particularly diarrhea, is killing over&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.who.int/philippines/news/feature-stories/detail/water-shortage-in-the-philippines-threatens-sustainable-development-and-health\">139 000 people</a>&nbsp;in the country ever year. If Covid-19 is now added to the list – as other studies have previously&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.sciencealert.com/latest-coronavirus-study-suggests-it-can-also-be-spread-through-poop\">warned</a>&nbsp;– fighting the virus effectively requires a wholistic approach that tackles the issue of reducing water pollution and providing alternative water supplies at the same time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The solution most city residents have been resorting to for years – in Manila and other cities across the ASEAN region – is the use of bottled water as a source of potable liquid independent of public supplies. Especially in times of public health emergencies like the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic, relying on bottled water is a safer option to prevent waterborne infections. As long as the government is&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.ibon.org/ensure-sufficient-safe-and-accessible-water-during-covid-19-crisis/\">unable</a>&nbsp;to guarantee “improved drinking water sources”, which the UN defines as “protected by outside contamination, particularly fecal matter”, this often remains the only option while deeper reforms to public infrastructure are being enacted.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','With merely one of 10 people in the Philippines having access to clean water','','inherit','closed','closed','','101-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:24:14','2020-06-29 16:24:14','',101,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/101-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(103,1,'2020-06-29 13:25:30','2020-06-29 16:25:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A new Cambodian government directive to end illegal logging is merely a “show” aimed at shedding its reputation of being too soft on forest crimes, indigenous groups and NGOs said on Thursday, a day after&nbsp;a survey by U.S. and EU monitors showed a major national forest lost&nbsp;more than one football pitch (1.76 acres) of woodlands every hour of 2019.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 19, Minister of Agriculture Veng Sakhon issued a statement asking all provincial agriculture directors to take action against illegal logging, land encroachment, and forest destruction according to the law.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Illegal fishing, illegal logging, and illegal encroachment on state land remarkably continues to exist in a few provinces, so in order to ensure effective management—especially of forests and fisheries—the Ministry of Agriculture calls on provincial and municipal agriculture officers to take action to prevent and crack down on [these violations] through any means necessary,” the statement said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The directive did not include any details about illegal logging or other forest crimes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Heng Sros, an activist with the group Lovers of the Environment, told RFA’s Khmer Service on Thursday that the ministry is “incapable” of addressing the problems it claims to be tackling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Even though the ministry wants to fix its reputation by issuing the statement, we activists see it as just a show that won’t result in action [on illegal logging],” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An indigenous villager from Mondulkiri province named&nbsp;Kroeung Tola called the statement “nothing new.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He said illegal logging is “in full swing right now,” including through state and communal land encroachment in the province—much of which is protected by local authorities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Illegal logging has continued nonstop on a daily basis under the protection of rich and powerful people,” he said. “Even if measures are taken, they will not be effective.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another villager in Ratanakiri province named&nbsp;Kham Nin told RFA he has no faith in the ministry to effectively implement the law because local authorities are the ones involved in forest crimes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He said that meanwhile, his local community forest is being destroyed and illegally occupied by speculators.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“The forest has become a desert because local authorities won’t implement the law according to the central government,” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“They collude with businessmen and disregard the law because they only care about money.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>RFA was unable to reach Minister Veng Sakhon for comment&nbsp;Thursday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bey Vanny, the coordinator for Cambodian rights group Adhoc in Stung Treng province, told RFA that he has only ever observed authorities crack down on illegal loggers who have no connection with powerful people, while letting those with money or government positions off the hook.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“We want the law to be applied equally because we have only ever observed action taken against the poor,” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Devastating deforestation</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Local authorities in Cambodia don’t only look the other way when forest crimes take place, they also regularly target environmental activists who are working to stop them from happening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In April, activists with Lovers of the Environment patrolling Prey Lang forest in Cambodia’s central plains said authorities interfered with their work and even tried to arrest them after they documented a local company conducting extensive illegal logging in the protected area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The University of Copenhagen said Wednesday that documentation which corresponds with satellite imagery from the EU Joint Research Centre and Global Land Analysis &amp; Discovery (GLAD) - University of Maryland&nbsp;showed that&nbsp;Cambodia lost the 10<sup>th</sup>most forest of any nation last year at 63,000 hectares (155,675 acres).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cambodia has lost 26 percent of its tree cover since 2000, it added, at an equivalent to 2.3 million hectares (5.7 million acres).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meanwhile, the university said, Prey Lang lost 7,510 hectares (18,560 acres) in 2019, which was a 73 percent increase from previous year and marked the highest rate of deforestation since 2016, when the sanctuary was declared.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Prey Lang lost more than one football pitch (1.76 acres) every hour in the entire year of 2019, it said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Official Order to End Illegal Logging Deemed ‘Show’ by Cambodian Activists','','publish','open','open','','official-order-to-end-illegal-logging-deemed-show-by-cambodian-activists','','','2020-06-30 11:14:02','2020-06-30 14:14:02','',0,'http://localhost/?p=103',0,'post','',0),(104,1,'2020-06-29 13:25:08','2020-06-29 16:25:08','','cambodia-2','','inherit','open','closed','','cambodia-2','','','2020-06-29 13:25:08','2020-06-29 16:25:08','',103,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/cambodia-2.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(105,1,'2020-06-29 13:25:30','2020-06-29 16:25:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A new Cambodian government directive to end illegal logging is merely a “show” aimed at shedding its reputation of being too soft on forest crimes, indigenous groups and NGOs said on Thursday, a day after&nbsp;a survey by U.S. and EU monitors showed a major national forest lost&nbsp;more than one football pitch (1.76 acres) of woodlands every hour of 2019.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 19, Minister of Agriculture Veng Sakhon issued a statement asking all provincial agriculture directors to take action against illegal logging, land encroachment, and forest destruction according to the law.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Illegal fishing, illegal logging, and illegal encroachment on state land remarkably continues to exist in a few provinces, so in order to ensure effective management—especially of forests and fisheries—the Ministry of Agriculture calls on provincial and municipal agriculture officers to take action to prevent and crack down on [these violations] through any means necessary,” the statement said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The directive did not include any details about illegal logging or other forest crimes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Heng Sros, an activist with the group Lovers of the Environment, told RFA’s Khmer Service on Thursday that the ministry is “incapable” of addressing the problems it claims to be tackling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Even though the ministry wants to fix its reputation by issuing the statement, we activists see it as just a show that won’t result in action [on illegal logging],” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An indigenous villager from Mondulkiri province named&nbsp;Kroeung Tola called the statement “nothing new.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He said illegal logging is “in full swing right now,” including through state and communal land encroachment in the province—much of which is protected by local authorities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Illegal logging has continued nonstop on a daily basis under the protection of rich and powerful people,” he said. “Even if measures are taken, they will not be effective.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another villager in Ratanakiri province named&nbsp;Kham Nin told RFA he has no faith in the ministry to effectively implement the law because local authorities are the ones involved in forest crimes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He said that meanwhile, his local community forest is being destroyed and illegally occupied by speculators.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“The forest has become a desert because local authorities won’t implement the law according to the central government,” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“They collude with businessmen and disregard the law because they only care about money.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>RFA was unable to reach Minister Veng Sakhon for comment&nbsp;Thursday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bey Vanny, the coordinator for Cambodian rights group Adhoc in Stung Treng province, told RFA that he has only ever observed authorities crack down on illegal loggers who have no connection with powerful people, while letting those with money or government positions off the hook.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“We want the law to be applied equally because we have only ever observed action taken against the poor,” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Devastating deforestation</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Local authorities in Cambodia don’t only look the other way when forest crimes take place, they also regularly target environmental activists who are working to stop them from happening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In April, activists with Lovers of the Environment patrolling Prey Lang forest in Cambodia’s central plains said authorities interfered with their work and even tried to arrest them after they documented a local company conducting extensive illegal logging in the protected area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The University of Copenhagen said Wednesday that documentation which corresponds with satellite imagery from the EU Joint Research Centre and Global Land Analysis &amp; Discovery (GLAD) - University of Maryland&nbsp;showed that&nbsp;Cambodia lost the 10<sup>th</sup>most forest of any nation last year at 63,000 hectares (155,675 acres).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cambodia has lost 26 percent of its tree cover since 2000, it added, at an equivalent to 2.3 million hectares (5.7 million acres).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meanwhile, the university said, Prey Lang lost 7,510 hectares (18,560 acres) in 2019, which was a 73 percent increase from previous year and marked the highest rate of deforestation since 2016, when the sanctuary was declared.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Prey Lang lost more than one football pitch (1.76 acres) every hour in the entire year of 2019, it said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Official Order to End Illegal Logging Deemed ‘Show’ by Cambodian Activists','','inherit','closed','closed','','103-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:25:30','2020-06-29 16:25:30','',103,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/103-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(106,1,'2020-06-29 13:28:09','2020-06-29 16:28:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The World Bank approved a $93 million credit for the Cambodia Land Allocation for Social and Economic Development scheme on Friday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The credit is slated to help improve the security of land tenure, infrastructure access and agricultural and social services for poor and landless people and indigenous communities in Cambodia.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Helping small farmers and rural communities to access land and natural resources in a sustainable and secure way is central to the Royal Government’s poverty reduction strategy,” said a World Bank press release.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It said the government has set up a legal framework for social land concessions that extends land tenure to landless and poor rural people.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The government also promotes the granting of land tenure rights to indigenous communities to extend their rights to land.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Access to land, better agriculture practices and extension services to improve productivity are crucial for the rural poor,” it said. The phase III project is known as LASED III.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“LASED III will help the government to continue providing land and land titles to landless and land-poor families and ensure land tenure security for indigenous communities in the project targeted areas,” World Bank country manager for Cambodia Inguna Dobraja said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The press release said LASED III will further expand the achievements of Phase I and Phase II in the implementation of the social land concession programme.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bank gives $93M for landless poor','','publish','open','open','','bank-gives-93m-for-landless-poor','','','2020-06-30 11:14:11','2020-06-30 14:14:11','',0,'http://localhost/?p=106',0,'post','',0),(107,1,'2020-06-29 13:26:22','2020-06-29 16:26:22','','','','inherit','open','closed','','cambodia3','','','2020-06-29 13:28:01','2020-06-29 16:28:01','',106,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/cambodia3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(108,1,'2020-06-29 13:28:09','2020-06-29 16:28:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The World Bank approved a $93 million credit for the Cambodia Land Allocation for Social and Economic Development scheme on Friday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The credit is slated to help improve the security of land tenure, infrastructure access and agricultural and social services for poor and landless people and indigenous communities in Cambodia.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Helping small farmers and rural communities to access land and natural resources in a sustainable and secure way is central to the Royal Government’s poverty reduction strategy,” said a World Bank press release.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It said the government has set up a legal framework for social land concessions that extends land tenure to landless and poor rural people.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The government also promotes the granting of land tenure rights to indigenous communities to extend their rights to land.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Access to land, better agriculture practices and extension services to improve productivity are crucial for the rural poor,” it said. The phase III project is known as LASED III.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“LASED III will help the government to continue providing land and land titles to landless and land-poor families and ensure land tenure security for indigenous communities in the project targeted areas,” World Bank country manager for Cambodia Inguna Dobraja said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The press release said LASED III will further expand the achievements of Phase I and Phase II in the implementation of the social land concession programme.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bank gives $93M for landless poor','','inherit','closed','closed','','106-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:28:09','2020-06-29 16:28:09','',106,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/106-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(109,1,'2020-06-29 13:29:23','2020-06-29 16:29:23','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The number of coffee plantations under the Lao Coffee Association (LCA) has decreased by around five to 10 per cent in the first five months of this year as growers shifted to cassava for better incomes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the price of Lao coffee falling and facing challenges posed by coffee larva, and types of&nbsp;<em>Polyphagozerra coffeae</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Acalolepta cervina</em>&nbsp;in recent years, some farmers have shifted from coffee to grow other commercial crops, LCA studies found.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the value of coffee exported by Laos increased as the price of local coffee beans was better this year, said LCA main coordinator Sivilay Xayasaeng.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the first five months of last year, Laos exported almost 12,000 tonnes of coffee worth around $24.9 million, and the figure increased this year to almost 20,000 tonnes worth $37 million. This year’s exports included the Arabica, Robusta, Exelsa and Roasted varieties.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the case of Arabica coffee, especially the red beans that companies in Laos bought from farmers, the highest price was 3,200 kip ($0.35) and the lowest price was 2,800 kip in December last year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the same time, the highest and lowest prices of white beans were 16,500 kip and 15,000 kip, respectively, while the prices for Robusta were 12,500 kip and 11,000 kip, respectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Vietnam is largest foreign market for Laos, accounting for 65 per cent of the total coffee exports, followed by Thailand, Japan, Cambodia, Belgium, Switzerland and the US.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Laos sees more revenue from coffee','','publish','open','open','','laos-sees-more-revenue-from-coffee','','','2020-06-30 11:14:22','2020-06-30 14:14:22','',0,'http://localhost/?p=109',0,'post','',0),(110,1,'2020-06-29 13:29:12','2020-06-29 16:29:12','Uma mulher coletando Cafe na Amazonia - Brazil','cambodia-4','','inherit','open','closed','','cambodia-4','','','2020-07-01 11:00:48','2020-07-01 14:00:48','',109,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/cambodia-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(111,1,'2020-06-29 13:29:23','2020-06-29 16:29:23','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The number of coffee plantations under the Lao Coffee Association (LCA) has decreased by around five to 10 per cent in the first five months of this year as growers shifted to cassava for better incomes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the price of Lao coffee falling and facing challenges posed by coffee larva, and types of&nbsp;<em>Polyphagozerra coffeae</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Acalolepta cervina</em>&nbsp;in recent years, some farmers have shifted from coffee to grow other commercial crops, LCA studies found.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the value of coffee exported by Laos increased as the price of local coffee beans was better this year, said LCA main coordinator Sivilay Xayasaeng.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the first five months of last year, Laos exported almost 12,000 tonnes of coffee worth around $24.9 million, and the figure increased this year to almost 20,000 tonnes worth $37 million. This year’s exports included the Arabica, Robusta, Exelsa and Roasted varieties.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the case of Arabica coffee, especially the red beans that companies in Laos bought from farmers, the highest price was 3,200 kip ($0.35) and the lowest price was 2,800 kip in December last year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the same time, the highest and lowest prices of white beans were 16,500 kip and 15,000 kip, respectively, while the prices for Robusta were 12,500 kip and 11,000 kip, respectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Vietnam is largest foreign market for Laos, accounting for 65 per cent of the total coffee exports, followed by Thailand, Japan, Cambodia, Belgium, Switzerland and the US.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Laos sees more revenue from coffee','','inherit','closed','closed','','109-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:29:23','2020-06-29 16:29:23','',109,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/109-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(112,1,'2020-06-29 13:30:47','2020-06-29 16:30:47','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NAKHON RATCHASIMA: About 100 people gathered in protest on Monday against a plan to build a garbage-fuelled power plant near their community in Khong district.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Villagers holding placards with messages opposing the planned power plant met at Wat Ban Muang&nbsp; Khong in tambon Khu Khat in the morning, before marching to rally in front of the office of the Khu Khat tambon administration organisation (TAO).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the TAO office, a meeting was in progress to consider steps to be taken to seek official permission for the construction of the power plant -&nbsp;a project to be jointly built and operated by a private company and the TAO.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The villagers submitted a protest letter and a list of people opposing the project to a representative of the chairman of the TAO.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They said that if the plant was built, there would be a dump for garbage brought from 19 nearby districts, just one kilometre from their community. The dump site was near a source of raw water for the production of tap&nbsp; water.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Villagers protest against planned garbage-fuelled power plant','','publish','open','open','','villagers-protest-against-planned-garbage-fuelled-power-plant','','','2020-06-30 11:09:32','2020-06-30 14:09:32','',0,'http://localhost/?p=112',0,'post','',0),(113,1,'2020-06-29 13:30:31','2020-06-29 16:30:31','','','','inherit','open','closed','','cambodia-5','','','2020-06-29 13:30:45','2020-06-29 16:30:45','',112,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/cambodia-5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(114,1,'2020-06-29 13:30:47','2020-06-29 16:30:47','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NAKHON RATCHASIMA: About 100 people gathered in protest on Monday against a plan to build a garbage-fuelled power plant near their community in Khong district.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Villagers holding placards with messages opposing the planned power plant met at Wat Ban Muang&nbsp; Khong in tambon Khu Khat in the morning, before marching to rally in front of the office of the Khu Khat tambon administration organisation (TAO).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the TAO office, a meeting was in progress to consider steps to be taken to seek official permission for the construction of the power plant -&nbsp;a project to be jointly built and operated by a private company and the TAO.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The villagers submitted a protest letter and a list of people opposing the project to a representative of the chairman of the TAO.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They said that if the plant was built, there would be a dump for garbage brought from 19 nearby districts, just one kilometre from their community. The dump site was near a source of raw water for the production of tap&nbsp; water.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Villagers protest against planned garbage-fuelled power plant','','inherit','closed','closed','','112-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:30:47','2020-06-29 16:30:47','',112,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/112-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(115,1,'2020-06-29 13:35:29','2020-06-29 16:35:29','<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-default\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"postLayout\":\"grid\",\"columns\":2,\"postsToShow\":2,\"categories\":[\"3\"],\"typeScale\":3} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"showAuthor\":false,\"postLayout\":\"grid\",\"categories\":[\"3\"],\"typeScale\":3} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:cover {\"customOverlayColor\":\"#cdde87\",\"className\":\"home__newsletter-bkg\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-cover has-background-dim home__newsletter-bkg\" style=\"background-color:#cdde87\"><div class=\"wp-block-cover__inner-container\"><!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column {\"width\":66.66} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\"><!-- wp:html -->\n<i class=\"far fa-newspaper home__newsletter-icon\"></i>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textColor\":\"primary\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"has-primary-color has-text-color\">WEEKLY NEWS DIGEST</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customTextColor\":\"#333333\"} -->\n<p style=\"color:#333333\" class=\"has-text-color\">Curating news, commentary and resources on development, its environmental and social impacts, and the context affecting the Mekong Region</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:shortcode -->\n[mc4wp_form id=\"65\"]\n<!-- /wp:shortcode --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column {\"width\":33.33} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\"><!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"secondary\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-secondary-color\"><strong>LATEST EDITION</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"right\",\"textColor\":\"primary-variation\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-text-align-right has-primary-variation-color\"><strong>No: 263</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":73,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/mkeye-6-768x432-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-73\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"secondary\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-secondary-color\"><strong>Título do conteúdo que geralmente será um nome grande</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:cover -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column {\"width\":70} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:70%\"><!-- wp:group -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">