 the Jrai ethnic minority in the Central Highlands&nbsp;province of Gia Lai pray for rain.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The annual ritual is held in early June in Rưng Ama Nin Village in Ayun Pa Town, in the southeast of the province, and is painstakingly prepared by a \'special council\' and attended by almost everyone in the area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The uniqueness of the celebrations is certain to delight visitors hoping to explore the mystic traditions of the Jrai.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Preparations began at the end of May in the small yard of villager Ro Com Hkliong’s house. The village council gathered for a meeting, with selected women villagers, to discuss plans for the ceremony.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike many other&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Praying for rain in a parched landscape','','publish','open','open','','praying-for-rain-in-a-parched-landscape','','','2020-06-29 13:56:55','2020-06-29 16:56:55','',0,'http://localhost/?p=140',0,'post','',0),(141,1,'2020-06-29 13:56:50','2020-06-29 16:56:50','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Quang Thái</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the summer sun is at its fiercest and all around is cracked and dried the Jrai ethnic minority in the Central Highlands&nbsp;province of Gia Lai pray for rain.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The annual ritual is held in early June in Rưng Ama Nin Village in Ayun Pa Town, in the southeast of the province, and is painstakingly prepared by a \'special council\' and attended by almost everyone in the area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The uniqueness of the celebrations is certain to delight visitors hoping to explore the mystic traditions of the Jrai.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Preparations began at the end of May in the small yard of villager Ro Com Hkliong’s house. The village council gathered for a meeting, with selected women villagers, to discuss plans for the ceremony.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike many other&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Praying for rain in a parched landscape','','inherit','closed','closed','','140-revision-v1','','','2020-06-29 13:56:50','2020-06-29 16:56:50','',140,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/29/140-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(142,1,'2020-06-29 13:57:27','2020-06-29 16:57:27','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The members of this group, which local people call the ceremonial “council”, must never have violated the village’s rules in the past, especially what is deemed taboo. He or she should also exert a positive influence on the community.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are certain acts that must be avoided at all costs on the day the ritual takes place, such as holding hoes or hammers or even going to work.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The offering, which is displayed for the main ritual, consists of a black boar without white spots and weighing about 20kg, and three jars of Jơbô wine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other items used in the ceremony include a large&nbsp;copper pan, five white porcelain bowls, and five bamboo straws for drinking<em>&nbsp;rượu cần&nbsp;</em>(wine stored in a big jar and drunk through long bamboo straws). All must only be used for the ritual, not daily life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At 9am, the ceremony began. Senior villager Ksor Hơ, who is also the chief celebrant and the host of the ceremony, slowly walked over and sat in front of&nbsp;three jars of wine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Senior villager Ksor ceremony','','publish','open','open','','senior-villager-ksor-ceremony','','','2020-06-30 11:01:51','2020-06-30 14:01:51','',0,'http://localhost/?p=142',0,'post','',0),(143,1,'2020-