INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (385,1,'2020-07-06 21:32:31','2020-07-07 00:32:31','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“These days, they are restless because they have to lose their source of livelihood that keeps their family alive,” said thirty-five-year-old Salman Adam, who represented tuna fishermen in Ternate, North Moluccas in a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://mdpi.or.id/images/pdf_list/publications_reports/202005_Laporan%20Rapid%20Assessment%20Dampak%20Covid-19%20terhadap%20Nelayan%20Tuna%20HL-MDPI-Final.pdf\">rapid assessment report</a>&nbsp;conducted by researchers of Masyarakat dan Perikanan Indonesia (MDPI) foundation. “Oh, Covid-19, be gone fast, we miss the normal tuna prices.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On a normal day, Adam would set off to catch tuna at around four in the morning and only return to shore at around seven in the evening, but the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic has now changed this habit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adam has ceased going to sea to fish since early March. Not because there are no tuna to catch, but because revenues from fishing could no longer offset operational costs. Persisting to fish now, would mean losing money.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“We no longer go out to fish. Fishing costs a lot, more than one million rupiah and just imagine that if we only get two or three fishes, that would not be able to cover our operational costs. That is why we just decided not to operate,” Adam told Ekuatorial on June 6, 2020.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since Covid-19 turned into a global pandemic, many countries have adopted a lockdown policy and consequently export markets shut down. Exporters could no longer export tuna to the United States for example, one the major takers of Indonesian tuna.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The price of tuna plunged. “The price of tuna has fallen drastically, from Rp 45,000 per kilogram to just Rp 18,000 per kilogram in Ternate,” lamented Adam. “I no longer get revenue at all as the tuna we sell is usually exported to the United States and at present, that is not possible.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The former Mission Director of the United States Agency for International Development (USAID) in Indonesia, Erin E. McKee was quoted on the official website of the Ministry of Marine and Fishery Affairs, as saying in April of 2019, the United States was Indonesia’s top tuna export destination.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2016, for example, Indonesia exported 1.2 million metric tons of tuna to the United States and in the following year, the United States imported $1 billion worth of Indonesian tuna.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Tuna Fishermen in Eastern Indonesia Struggling Amidst Dropping Demand, Crippled Export','','publish','open','open','','tuna-fishermen-in-eastern-indonesia-struggling-amidst-dropping-demand-crippled-export','','','2020-07-06 21:32:43','2020-07-07 00:32:43','',0,'http://localhost/?p=385',0,'post','',0),(386,1,'2020-07-06 21:32:25','2020-07-07 00:32:25','','ek-story-1','','inherit','open','closed','','ek-story-1','','','2020-07-06 21:32:25','2020-07-07 00:32:25','',385,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek-story-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(387,1,'2020-07-06 21:32:31','2020-07-07 00:32:31','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“These days, they are restless because they have to lose their source of livelihood that keeps their family alive,” said thirty-five-year-old Salman Adam, who represented tuna fishermen in Ternate, North Moluccas in a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://mdpi.or.id/images/pdf_list/publications_reports/202005_Laporan%20Rapid%20Assessment%20Dampak%20Covid-19%20terhadap%20Nelayan%20Tuna%20HL-MDPI-Final.pdf\">rapid assessment report</a>&nbsp;conducted by researchers of Masyarakat dan Perikanan Indonesia (MDPI) foundation. “Oh, Covid-19, be gone fast, we miss the normal tuna prices.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On a normal day, Adam would set off to catch tuna at around four in the morning and only return to shore at around seven in the evening, but the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic has now changed this habit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adam has ceased going to sea to fish since early March. Not because there are no tuna to catch, but because revenues from fishing could no longer offset operational costs. Persisting to fish now, would mean losing money.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“We no longer go out to fish. Fishing costs a lot, more than one million rupiah and just imagine that if we only get two or three fishes, that would not be able to cover our operational costs. That is why we just decided not to operate,” Adam told Ekuatorial on June 6, 2020.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since Covid-19 turned into a global pandemic, many countries have adopted a lockdown policy and consequently export markets shut down. Exporters could no longer export tuna to the United States for example, one the major takers of Indonesian tuna.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The price of tuna plunged. “The price of tuna has fallen drastically, from Rp 45,000 per kilogram to just Rp 18,000 per kilogram in Ternate,” lamented Adam. “I no longer get revenue at all as the tuna we sell is usually exported to the United States and at present, that is not possible.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The former Mission Director of the United States Agency for International Development (USAID) in Indonesia, Erin E. McKee was quoted on the official website of the Ministry of Marine and Fishery Affairs, as saying in April of 2019, the United States was Indonesia’s top tuna export destination.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2016, for example, Indonesia exported 1.2 million metric tons of tuna to the United States and in the following year, the United States imported $1 billion worth of Indonesian tuna.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Tuna Fishermen in Eastern Indonesia Struggling Amidst Dropping Demand, Crippled Export','','inherit','closed','closed','','385-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:32:31','2020-07-07 00:32:31','',385,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/385-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(388,1,'2020-07-06 21:33:45','2020-07-07 00:33:45','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Maluku Province in far eastern Indonesia, an increasingly erratic climate has left clove farmers unable to depend on the spice that put this region on the map.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The sun that beat down on Ambon Island in the middle of January was intense, with temperatures reaching as high as 34 degrees Celsius.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Irawan Ruhuputty, 33, a farmer in&nbsp; Negeri Tial in Ambon, Central Maluku, pointed to a dried-out clove tree on the verge of death. Most of its leaves had fallen off, with only brownish-yellow ones remaining.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I don’t know whether this is caused by a disease or it’s too hot. If this happens, [the tree] will usually die,” Irawan said during an interview in January.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cloves are native to the Maluku Islands.&nbsp;They grow naturally from the shoreline far into the mountains and are not cultivated in plantations like other commodities, such as palm oil.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clove as well as nutmeg have an important meaning for the people of Maluku.&nbsp;Before the 18th century, all the world’s clove and nutmeg supplies only came from this part of Indonesia, better known by traders as the Spice Islands.&nbsp;Because of their importance, the people of Maluku would store their crops as collateral, selling them only when there was an urgent need or when they wanted to finance a big celebration, such as a wedding.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, in recent years it has become increasingly difficult for farmers to horde their cloves, let alone fulfill their daily needs.&nbsp;Annual clove yields are no longer certain.&nbsp;In a good year farmers can earn tens of millions of rupiah, but more often they can barely cover the costs of the labor needed to harvest the cloves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the September 2019 harvest, Irwan’s family was only able to collect about 10 kilograms of cloves on their roughly one hectare of land, said Irwan’s father, 54-year-old Thalib Ruhuputty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Clove farmers in Indonesia’s ‘Spice Islands’ face increasing uncertainty in a changing climate','','publish','open','open','','clove-farmers-in-indonesias-spice-islands-face-increasing-uncertainty-in-a-changing-climate','','','2020-07-06 21:40:21','2020-07-07 00:40:21','',0,'http://localhost/?p=388',0,'post','',0),(389,1,'2020-07-06 21:33:35','2020-07-07 00:33:35','','','','inherit','open','closed','','ek-story-2','','','2020-07-06 21:33:43','2020-07-07 00:33:43','',388,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek-story-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(390,1,'2020-07-06 21:33:45','2020-07-07 00:33:45','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Maluku Province in far eastern Indonesia, an increasingly erratic climate has left clove farmers unable to depend on the spice that put this region on the map.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The sun that beat down on Ambon Island in the middle of January was intense, with temperatures reaching as high as 34 degrees Celsius.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Irawan Ruhuputty, 33, a farmer in&nbsp; Negeri Tial in Ambon, Central Maluku, pointed to a dried-out clove tree on the verge of death. Most of its leaves had fallen off, with only brownish-yellow ones remaining.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I don’t know whether this is caused by a disease or it’s too hot. If this happens, [the tree] will usually die,” Irawan said during an interview in January.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cloves are native to the Maluku Islands.&nbsp;They grow naturally from the shoreline far into the mountains and are not cultivated in plantations like other commodities, such as palm oil.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clove as well as nutmeg have an important meaning for the people of Maluku.&nbsp;Before the 18th century, all the world’s clove and nutmeg supplies only came from this part of Indonesia, better known by traders as the Spice Islands.&nbsp;Because of their importance, the people of Maluku would store their crops as collateral, selling them only when there was an urgent need or when they wanted to finance a big celebration, such as a wedding.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, in recent years it has become increasingly difficult for farmers to horde their cloves, let alone fulfill their daily needs.&nbsp;Annual clove yields are no longer certain.&nbsp;In a good year farmers can earn tens of millions of rupiah, but more often they can barely cover the costs of the labor needed to harvest the cloves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the September 2019 harvest, Irwan’s family was only able to collect about 10 kilograms of cloves on their roughly one hectare of land, said Irwan’s father, 54-year-old Thalib Ruhuputty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Clove farmers in Indonesia’s ‘Spice Islands’ face increasing uncertainty in a changing climate','','inherit','closed','closed','','388-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:33:45','2020-07-07 00:33:45','',388,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/388-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(391,1,'2020-07-06 21:34:45','2020-07-07 00:34:45','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fisherman Nanang drove us in his boat down the Bengawan Solo River in Gresik Regency. Near the sea, he turned off the ship’s engine. “The anchors go down,” Nanang said. “It’s very shallow, don’t get trapped, you can’t go home later.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the start of the rainy season this year, the Bengawan Solo River here in East Java, Indonesia, is clean at first glance. It’s brown, the color of ordinary river water. Traces of plastic rubbish leftover from the dry season are visible on the river’s banks and in the mangroves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Try to come during the dry season,” said Nanang, “boats cannot pass.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nanang lives in Ujung Pangkah, a village at the end of the Bengawan Solo River, just before it enters the Java Sea. Every dry season he witnesses rubbish covering the surface of the river, making it difficult for fishermen to go to sea.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the rainy season, trash drifts into the sea until it ends up on the beaches in Bali to the east, Nanang said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to data from the Ocean Cleanup Project provided by Resource Watch, an open-data visualization platform, 32,500 tonnes of plastic waste from Bengawan Solo enter the ocean each year. Three other rivers in Java are also of concern for the amount they contribute to ocean pollution. They are the Brantas River, in East Java, with 38,900 tonnes of garbage per year; the Serayu River, in Central Java, with 17,100 tonnes; and the Progo River, in Yogyakarta, with 12,800 tonnes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Plastic Trash Runs Down the Solo River to Pollute the Java Sea','','publish','open','open','','plastic-trash-runs-down-the-solo-river-to-pollute-the-java-sea','','','2020-07-06 21:34:50','2020-07-07 00:34:50','',0,'http://localhost/?p=391',0,'post','',0),(392,1,'2020-07-06 21:34:33','2020-07-07 00:34:33','','ek-story-3','','inherit','open','closed','','ek-story-3','','','2020-07-06 21:34:33','2020-07-07 00:34:33','',391,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek-story-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(393,1,'2020-07-06 21:34:45','2020-07-07 00:34:45','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fisherman Nanang drove us in his boat down the Bengawan Solo River in Gresik Regency. Near the sea, he turned off the ship’s engine. “The anchors go down,” Nanang said. “It’s very shallow, don’t get trapped, you can’t go home later.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the start of the rainy season this year, the Bengawan Solo River here in East Java, Indonesia, is clean at first glance. It’s brown, the color of ordinary river water. Traces of plastic rubbish leftover from the dry season are visible on the river’s banks and in the mangroves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Try to come during the dry season,” said Nanang, “boats cannot pass.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nanang lives in Ujung Pangkah, a village at the end of the Bengawan Solo River, just before it enters the Java Sea. Every dry season he witnesses rubbish covering the surface of the river, making it difficult for fishermen to go to sea.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the rainy season, trash drifts into the sea until it ends up on the beaches in Bali to the east, Nanang said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to data from the Ocean Cleanup Project provided by Resource Watch, an open-data visualization platform, 32,500 tonnes of plastic waste from Bengawan Solo enter the ocean each year. Three other rivers in Java are also of concern for the amount they contribute to ocean pollution. They are the Brantas River, in East Java, with 38,900 tonnes of garbage per year; the Serayu River, in Central Java, with 17,100 tonnes; and the Progo River, in Yogyakarta, with 12,800 tonnes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Plastic Trash Runs Down the Solo River to Pollute the Java Sea','','inherit','closed','closed','','391-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:34:45','2020-07-07 00:34:45','',391,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/391-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(394,1,'2020-07-06 21:35:30','2020-07-07 00:35:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bengawan Solo, the longest river on Indonesia’s main island of Java, has sweet memories for 45-year-old Suryanto. He used to bathe in it nightly alongside other friends from Gawan Village, one of many villages in Java that rely on the river as their prime source of water.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the past 20 years, however, villagers have rarely gone down to the river for washing Suryanto said. Industrial and household waste along with farm waste such as pig and chicken carcasses have polluted the river, killing off much of its aquatic life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“People used to look for fish here, but now they don’t exist. Now it’s dirty. Even small fish can die from waste,” Suryanto told Tirto.id in early February.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>More recently, pollution has prevented municipal water supply companies from using the river as a source of raw water, forcing residents to buy treated water instead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bengawan Solo: A River Full of Plastic Waste, Diapers, Animal Carcasses','','publish','open','open','','bengawan-solo-a-river-full-of-plastic-waste-diapers-animal-carcasses','','','2020-07-06 21:36:11','2020-07-07 00:36:11','',0,'http://localhost/?p=394',0,'post','',0),(395,1,'2020-07-06 21:35:30','2020-07-07 00:35:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bengawan Solo, the longest river on Indonesia’s main island of Java, has sweet memories for 45-year-old Suryanto. He used to bathe in it nightly alongside other friends from Gawan Village, one of many villages in Java that rely on the river as their prime source of water.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the past 20 years, however, villagers have rarely gone down to the river for washing Suryanto said. Industrial and household waste along with farm waste such as pig and chicken carcasses have polluted the river, killing off much of its aquatic life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“People used to look for fish here, but now they don’t exist. Now it’s dirty. Even small fish can die from waste,” Suryanto told Tirto.id in early February.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>More recently, pollution has prevented municipal water supply companies from using the river as a source of raw water, forcing residents to buy treated water instead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bengawan Solo: A River Full of Plastic Waste, Diapers, Animal Carcasses','','inherit','closed','closed','','394-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:35:30','2020-07-07 00:35:30','',394,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/394-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(396,1,'2020-07-06 21:36:01','2020-07-07 00:36:01','','ek-story-4','','inherit','open','closed','','ek-story-4','','','2020-07-06 21:36:01','2020-07-07 00:36:01','',394,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek-story-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(397,1,'2020-07-06 21:37:04','2020-07-07 00:37:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dawn had not yet broken in Cileungsi, Bogor, when 31-year-old Widya Astuti, 36, was already on her way to work at the Sulianti Saroso Hospital for Infectious Diseases in the Sunter area of North Jakarta. Astuti, is a nurse.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I wake up at three thirty. I then hold my prayer and then prepare breakfast at home. After morning prayer’s time, around five or five thirty, I leave, board a public transport, If it happens that my husband also has to leave at the same time, then I will go with him,” Astuti told Ekuatorial on Wednesday (1/4).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She spends half her day for work, a fourth for her family and another fourth to rest. At home Astuti still has to care for her children who are still in primary school.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I get home around six or seven in the evening. Once I got home, again I put order into the house such as washing the dishes, or helping my children do what they have to do, or other things, I would sleep early because I usually am already tired by then,” she said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the Sulianti Saroso hospital, Astuti works at the isolation room with 28 other nurses, The Covid-19 pandemic is making her busy with the intense monitoring and caring of patients. She also has to continuously record her patients’ vitals such as blood pressure, heartbeats, and body temperature.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Astuti also must make sure that the needs of the patients are also met. She sometimes has to spoon fed patients or help them get to the bathroom.&nbsp;“One nurse takes care of two patients,” she said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Pandemic Heightens Women’s Vulnerability','','publish','open','open','','pandemic-heightens-womens-vulnerability','','','2020-07-06 21:37:11','2020-07-07 00:37:11','',0,'http://localhost/?p=397',0,'post','',0),(398,1,'2020-07-06 21:36:48','2020-07-07 00:36:48','','Ek5','','inherit','open','closed','','ek5','','','2020-07-06 21:36:48','2020-07-07 00:36:48','',397,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Ek5.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(399,1,'2020-07-06 21:37:04','2020-07-07 00:37:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dawn had not yet broken in Cileungsi, Bogor, when 31-year-old Widya Astuti, 36, was already on her way to work at the Sulianti Saroso Hospital for Infectious Diseases in the Sunter area of North Jakarta. Astuti, is a nurse.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I wake up at three thirty. I then hold my prayer and then prepare breakfast at home. After morning prayer’s time, around five or five thirty, I leave, board a public transport, If it happens that my husband also has to leave at the same time, then I will go with him,” Astuti told Ekuatorial on Wednesday (1/4).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She spends half her day for work, a fourth for her family and another fourth to rest. At home Astuti still has to care for her children who are still in primary school.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I get home around six or seven in the evening. Once I got home, again I put order into the house such as washing the dishes, or helping my children do what they have to do, or other things, I would sleep early because I usually am already tired by then,” she said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the Sulianti Saroso hospital, Astuti works at the isolation room with 28 other nurses, The Covid-19 pandemic is making her busy with the intense monitoring and caring of patients. She also has to continuously record her patients’ vitals such as blood pressure, heartbeats, and body temperature.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Astuti also must make sure that the needs of the patients are also met. She sometimes has to spoon fed patients or help them get to the bathroom.&nbsp;“One nurse takes care of two patients,” she said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Pandemic Heightens Women’s Vulnerability','','inherit','closed','closed','','397-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:37:04','2020-07-07 00:37:04','',397,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/397-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(400,1,'2020-07-06 21:38:35','2020-07-07 00:38:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Rejang Lebong, BENGKULU.&nbsp;</strong>Rita Wati (51), Purwani (48) and Feni Oktaviana (22), sat in the shade under a canopy of trees after conducting a patrol in an area of the Kerinci Seblat National Park (TNKS). The three women from Pal VIII village in the Bengkulu district of Rejang Lebong, were resting, enjoying the light breeze and the chirping of birds. The sound of insects could also be heard in the background.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“This is one of our routine group activities,” said Rita who chairs the “Maju Bersama”, a women’s group for the environment, or locally known as KPPL, of Pal VIII village. The Maju Bersama KPPL conducts such patrols at least once a month, patrols that help to prevent illegal logging, land grabbing or any other activities that could damage forest areas in the TNKS. “Forests are sources of life, livelihood and knowledge for women, therefore, the forest should be protected,” said Wati.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Besides patrolling, the Maju Bersama KPPL also provides public education about the national park, area restoration and the utilisation of the&nbsp;<em>Kecombrang</em>&nbsp;plant (Etlingera elatior or ginger torch) and ferns (Diplazium esculentum), within a 10-hectare plot of the forest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These activities were made possible following the signing of a conservation partnership, between Maju Bersama and TNKS, on&nbsp; March 5, 2019. This partnership agreement made the Maju Bersama KPPL the first women’s group in Indonesia to successfully fight for the rights to participate in forest conservation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Maju Bersama, Pioneering Rural Women Participation in Forest Conservation','','publish','open','open','','maju-bersama-pioneering-rural-women-participation-in-forest-conservation','','','2020-07-06 21:38:40','2020-07-07 00:38:40','',0,'http://localhost/?p=400',0,'post','',0),(401,1,'2020-07-06 21:38:07','2020-07-07 00:38:07','','ek6','','inherit','open','closed','','ek6','','','2020-07-06 21:38:07','2020-07-07 00:38:07','',400,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek6.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(402,1,'2020-07-06 21:38:35','2020-07-07 00:38:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Rejang Lebong, BENGKULU.&nbsp;</strong>Rita Wati (51), Purwani (48) and Feni Oktaviana (22), sat in the shade under a canopy of trees after conducting a patrol in an area of the Kerinci Seblat National Park (TNKS). The three women from Pal VIII village in the Bengkulu district of Rejang Lebong, were resting, enjoying the light breeze and the chirping of birds. The sound of insects could also be heard in the background.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“This is one of our routine group activities,” said Rita who chairs the “Maju Bersama”, a women’s group for the environment, or locally known as KPPL, of Pal VIII village. The Maju Bersama KPPL conducts such patrols at least once a month, patrols that help to prevent illegal logging, land grabbing or any other activities that could damage forest areas in the TNKS. “Forests are sources of life, livelihood and knowledge for women, therefore, the forest should be protected,” said Wati.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Besides patrolling, the Maju Bersama KPPL also provides public education about the national park, area restoration and the utilisation of the&nbsp;<em>Kecombrang</em>&nbsp;plant (Etlingera elatior or ginger torch) and ferns (Diplazium esculentum), within a 10-hectare plot of the forest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These activities were made possible following the signing of a conservation partnership, between Maju Bersama and TNKS, on&nbsp; March 5, 2019. This partnership agreement made the Maju Bersama KPPL the first women’s group in Indonesia to successfully fight for the rights to participate in forest conservation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Maju Bersama, Pioneering Rural Women Participation in Forest Conservation','','inherit','closed','closed','','400-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:38:35','2020-07-07 00:38:35','',400,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/400-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(403,1,'2020-07-06 21:39:35','2020-07-07 00:39:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Committee for the Phasing Out of Leaded Fuel (KPBB) – a non-governmental organization dealing with air quality issues– had already predicted this condition, linking it to the restriction on activities and movements in the capital, the epicenter of the new Corona virus (SARS-CoV-2) in the country, aimed at slowing down its spread.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“We predicted that in the first ten days (of the restriction on activity and movement) there would be a drop (in air pollution.) Therefore, we dared to predict (more drop). It is actually logical, with social distancing even though at the time it was not yet enforced on a large scale, it would mean a drop in activities, in transportation, the industry or the service sector such as in hotels, restaurant and tourism. They clearly would drop,” KPBB Director Ahmad Syafruddin told Ekuatorial.com, on Saturday (11/4).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But an analysis by KPBB showed that in the first ten days of the Large Scale Social Restriction (PSBB) or the March 16-25 period, air quality in Jakarta remains within an unhealthy category, with PM2.5 concentration averaging 44.55 µg/m3. The figure was obtain from an ambient air quality monitoring conducted by the US Embassy, and also monitoring of air quality at several points.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A marked difference was recorded when entering the second ten-day period of the restriction, or the March 26- April 4 period. Air pollution dropped significantly that air quality approached a healthier category. PM2.5 concentration showed an annual average of 18.46 µg/m3. Under the current government standard stipulated in Government Regulation Number 41 of 1999 on Air Pollution Control, the healthy standard for PM2.5 concentration is set at 15 µg/m3.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','What Lies Beyond the Clear Sky of Jakarta During the Covid-19 Pandemic','','publish','open','open','','what-lies-beyond-the-clear-sky-of-jakarta-during-the-covid-19-pandemic','','','2020-07-06 23:00:30','2020-07-07 02:00:30','',0,'http://localhost/?p=403',0,'post','',0),(404,1,'2020-07-06 21:39:07','2020-07-07 00:39:07','','ek','','inherit','open','closed','','ek','','','2020-07-06 21:39:07','2020-07-07 00:39:07','',403,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/ek.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(405,1,'2020-07-06 21:39:35','2020-07-07 00:39:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Committee for the Phasing Out of Leaded Fuel (KPBB) – a non-governmental organization dealing with air quality issues– had already predicted this condition, linking it to the restriction on activities and movements in the capital, the epicenter of the new Corona virus (SARS-CoV-2) in the country, aimed at slowing down its spread.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“We predicted that in the first ten days (of the restriction on activity and movement) there would be a drop (in air pollution.) Therefore, we dared to predict (more drop). It is actually logical, with social distancing even though at the time it was not yet enforced on a large scale, it would mean a drop in activities, in transportation, the industry or the service sector such as in hotels, restaurant and tourism. They clearly would drop,” KPBB Director Ahmad Syafruddin told Ekuatorial.com, on Saturday (11/4).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But an analysis by KPBB showed that in the first ten days of the Large Scale Social Restriction (PSBB) or the March 16-25 period, air quality in Jakarta remains within an unhealthy category, with PM2.5 concentration averaging 44.55 µg/m3. The figure was obtain from an ambient air quality monitoring conducted by the US Embassy, and also monitoring of air quality at several points.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A marked difference was recorded when entering the second ten-day period of the restriction, or the March 26- April 4 period. Air pollution dropped significantly that air quality approached a healthier category. PM2.5 concentration showed an annual average of 18.46 µg/m3. Under the current government standard stipulated in Government Regulation Number 41 of 1999 on Air Pollution Control, the healthy standard for PM2.5 concentration is set at 15 µg/m3.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','What Lies Beyond the Clear Sky of Jakarta During the Covid-19 Pandemic','','inherit','closed','closed','','403-revision-v1','','','2020-07-06 21:39:35','2020-07-07 00:39:35','',403,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/07/06/403-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(408,1,'2020-07-06 21:48:28','2020-07-07 00:48:28','<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column {\"width\":25} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:25%\"><!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-default\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"postsToShow\":2,\"typeScale\":2,\"sectionHeader\":\"MAPS\"} /--></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column {\"width\":50} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:50%\"><!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-default\",\"showAuthor\":false,\"categories\":[\"25\"],\"typeScale\":3,\"sectionHeader\":\"LATEST NEWS\"} /--></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column {\"width\":25} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:25%\"><!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-default\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"postsToShow\":1,\"categories\":[\"26\"],\"typeScale\":2,\"sectionHeader\":\"COVID-19\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-default\",\"showExc